Ed,<br><br>
Pushing the envelope means the same to me.  Problem is I enjoyed it way too much.  Flew for more than one service both in uniform and out.  Reality cut in the fall of 1994 and I stood down.  Still the ego serves.  I am sure you know what I mean.   Numbed yes, even over the edge was no longer much of a rush.  Certain thoughts would creep in at the absolute limit which tempted me to taste the point of no return.  Fear is nice.  You don't know how much you need it until it is gone.<br><br>
As for being fondled.  You are the last one I expected that statement from.  I am not a sycophant and I am not looking for one.  If I want a pet I'll buy a dog.  <br><br>
LZ is certainly no pet, but I think I did piss him off.  Wished I hadn't done that.  His insults mean nothing.  I have been insulted by real pros in my time. Unfortunately like you I am capable of some real venom.  I just have a very slow fuse.  Something our profession requires.  Anger always weakens your position and creates terminal mistakes.  LZ knows that, but he didn't expect to push your buttons.   He is for real.  Obviously doesn't like Doc, but does think a lot of you or a least did before this emotional explosion.<br><br>
He is target focused.  I think the Doc knows that by now.<br><br>
I deeply appreciate the protective stance.  It will not be forgotten.
<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


